INSERT INTO `guidedetail` (`id`, `variable`, `video`, `description`) VALUES
(1, 'pH', 'BwmPDNa9ZoI', 'Step for Testing pH Levels Using a pH Meter\n\n1. Unbox the pH Meter:\n-Open the package to find the pH tester.\n-Note that it has two buttons: one for power and the other for calibration.\n\n2. Prepare Calibration Solution (Optional):\n-If calibration is needed, use the provided pH calibration packets.\n-Mix each packet in separate cups of water to avoid contamination.\n-Follow the instructions for calibration if required.\n\n3. Turn On the pH Meter:\n-Press the power button to turn the device on.\n\n4. Prepare the Water Sample:\n-Pour the water you want to test (tap water, bottled water, etc.) into a clean cup.\n-Fill the cup just enough to submerge the tip of the pH meter.\n\n5. Test the Water:\n-Remove the protective cap from the pH meter.\n-Dip the probe into the water sample. Do not submerge the entire meter, just the sensor tip.\n-Stir gently to allow the meter to stabilize.\n\n6. Read the pH Level:\n-Wait for the reading to stabilize on the display.\n-Record the pH level of the water.\n\n7. Test Additional Samples (Optional):\n-If testing another water source, rinse and dry the probe before repeating the process.\n\n8. Turn Off and Store:\n-After testing, turn off the device and replace the cap on the sensor to protect it.\n\n8. Maintain the pH Meter:\n-Periodically calibrate the pH meter using the provided calibration solutions to ensure accuracy.'),
(2, 'Hardness', 'uMYJ-o0TUVs', 'Step for Testing Water Hardness Using Test Strip\r\n\r\n1. Prepare the Test Area:\r\n-Find a clean, small cup or container to collect water. Around 1-2 inches of water is needed in the container.\r\n\r\n2. Select Water Sources:\r\n-For Hard Water: Collect water from an unfiltered source. Common options include:\r\nAn outdoor spigot.\r\n-For Soft Water: Collect water from an indoor soft water source like:\r\nAny hot water tap (kitchen or bathroom).\r\n\r\n3. Use the Test Strip:\r\n-Take a test strip from the water hardness test kit.\r\n-Dip the test strip into the collected water for about 2 seconds.\r\n\r\n4. Remove the Strip and Shake:\r\n-After dipping the strip, remove it from the water.\r\n-Gently shake off any excess water.\r\n\r\n5. Wait for Results:\r\n-Let the strip sit for about 15 seconds to allow the color to develop.\r\n\r\n6. Compare the Results:\r\n-Match the color on the test strip to the color chart provided with the kit.\r\n-Typical hardness ranges include:\r\n0-25 ppm: Soft water\r\n25-50 ppm: Moderately soft water\r\n50-120 ppm: Slightly hard water\r\n120-250 ppm: Moderately hard water\r\n250+ ppm: Hard to very hard water\r\n\r\nInterpret the Results:\r\n-For outdoor (unfiltered) water, expect a high number if the water is hard.\r\n-For indoor (softened) water, the reading should be significantly lower, ideally under 50 ppm, which is considered soft.'),
(3, 'Solids', '2kyraksGxYE', 'Step for Testing Water Solids Using the TDS Meter\r\n\r\n1. Prepare the Test Area:\r\n-Fill a clean glass or container with around 2 inches of water to test.\r\n\r\n2. Rinse the Meter:\r\n-Before testing, rinse the sensors on the bottom of the meter with purified water (from your system) to avoid contamination.\r\n-Shake off any excess water droplets.\r\n\r\n3. Take the First Reading (Purified Water):\r\n-Turn on the meter using the power button.\r\n-Place the meter\'s sensors into the glass of purified water.\r\n-Lightly stir the meter to dislodge any air bubbles.\r\n-Wait 20 seconds for the reading to stabilize.\r\n-Press the Hold button to lock the reading.\r\n-Remove the meter from the water and write down the TDS reading displayed on the screen.\r\n-If the x10 symbol is flashing, multiply the reading by 10.\r\n\r\n4. Take the Second Reading (Tap Water):\r\n-Rinse the meter again in purified water, and shake off excess droplets.\r\n-Fill another glass with around 2 inches of tap water.\r\n-Turn on the meter and place the sensors into the glass of tap water.\r\n-Lightly stir to dislodge air bubbles.\r\n-Wait 20 seconds for the reading to stabilize.\r\n-Press the Hold button and write down the reading.\r\n-If the x10 symbol is flashing, multiply the reading by 10.\r\n\r\n5. Calculate the TDS Reduction:\r\n-Use the two readings (purified and tap water) to determine the TDS reduction percentage.\r\nFormula:\r\nTDS Reduction = ((Tap Water TDS − Purified Water TDS) / (Tap Water TDS)) × 100\r\n\r\nExample: If tap water has a TDS reading of 500 and purified water reads 40, the reduction is calculated as: 92%\r\n\r\n6. Determine When to Replace the Membrane\r\n-The RO membrane should be replaced when the TDS reduction falls below 80%.\r\n-Using the example above, if the purified water TDS reading reaches 100, the membrane needs to be replaced.'),
(4, 'Chloramines', 'zzoPOHQ9FMY', 'Step for Testing Chloramines Using a Free Chlorine and Total Chlorine Meter\n\nFor testing chloramines, it\'s essential to understand the relationship between free chlorine, total chlorine, and chloramines.\n\nTotal Chlorine Test (Steps similar to Free Chlorine)\n1. Prepare the Meter: \n-Insert the battery and turn on the meter, similar to the free chlorine test.\n\n2. Prepare the Sample: \n-Fill the cuvette with the water sample and wipe the outside to ensure no smudges or bubbles.\n\n3. Zero the Meter: \n-Insert the cuvette into the meter and press the button to zero it (just like the free chlorine test).\n\n4. Add Total Chlorine Reagent: \n-Remove the cuvette, add the reagent for total chlorine (different from the free chlorine reagent), invert the cuvette to mix, and reinsert it into the meter.\n\n5. Start the Reaction Timer: \n-Hold the button for 3 seconds to start the timer. When the countdown ends, the meter will automatically take the measurement.\n\n6. Record the Result: \n-Once the reaction is complete, the meter will display the total chlorine value.\n\nChloramine Calculation:\n-To calculate the chloramine concentration:\n\nChloramines = Total Chlorine - Free Chlorine\n\nIf you\'ve already measured both free chlorine and total chlorine using the steps above, subtract the free chlorine value from the total chlorine value to get the chloramine concentration.\n\n-For example:\nTotal Chlorine: 3.0 ppm\nFree Chlorine: 1.5 ppm\nChloramines: 1.5 ppm (3.0 - 1.5)'),
(5, 'Sulfate', '1dsaz71BB8o', 'Step for Hach 225100 Sulfate Test Kit:\r\n\r\nThis method is straightforward and similar to other titration-based kits like the Hanna Instruments Sulfate Kit (video above). The main differences are in specific reagents and the concentration ranges they cover, but the basic procedure of reagent addition, titration, and comparison remains consistent.\r\n\r\n1. Collect Sample:\r\n-Gather the water sample to be tested in a clean container.\r\n\r\n2. Prepare the Sample:\r\n-Add a measured volume of the water sample into a titration vessel.\r\n\r\n3.Add Reagents:\r\n-The kit will provide sulfate reagents, including barium chloride. Add the specified amount of reagent to the sample. This reacts with sulfate ions to form barium sulfate, causing turbidity (cloudiness).\r\n\r\n4. Titration Process:\r\n-The sample is titrated with a solution provided in the kit. Titration involves adding the solution drop by drop until a color change indicates the endpoint.\r\nThis color change correlates with the sulfate concentration in the sample.\r\n\r\n5. Determine the Result:\r\nAfter the endpoint is reached, the sulfate concentration is determined by reading the corresponding value on the titration chart or using the number of titrants drops added.\r\n\r\n6. Interpret the Results:\r\n-Compare the obtained result with the kit’s reference chart to determine sulfate levels in ppm (parts per million).\r\nconsistent.'),
(6, 'Conductivity', 'KtlmV0JVOMA', 'Steps for Conductivity Testing Using HoneForest Meter:\r\n\r\n1. Turn on the Device: \r\n-Press and hold the power button.\r\n\r\n2. Switch to Conductivity Mode (EC): \r\n-Tap the button to cycle through the different modes (TDS, EC, Temp). Choose EC mode to test the conductivity.\r\n\r\n3. Test the Water:\r\n-Submerge the testing end of the device into the water sample.\r\n-Allow the reading to stabilize. The tester will provide a value in microSiemens per centimeter (µS/cm).\r\n\r\n4. Interpret the Results: \r\n- Compare the EC reading with recommended values for safe drinking water. Generally, an EC value of less than 400 µS/cm is considered good, as stated by the World Health Organization.'),
(7, 'Organic_carbon', 'YBdSlQor8OM', 'Steps for Testing Water Quality Using Envig TOC Meter\r\n\r\n1. Prepare the Water Sample: \r\n-Pour a sample of tap water (or any other water you\'re testing) into a clean container.\r\n\r\n2. Insert the Probe: \r\n-Place the probe of the TOC meter into the water sample. Make sure the probe is fully submerged and that there are no bubbles attached to the probe, as this can affect the readings.\r\n\r\n3. Turn On the Meter: \r\n-Press the power button to activate the meter.\r\n\r\n4. Initiate the Test:\r\n-Press the button to begin measuring the TOC value.\r\n-The device will display readings, which may fluctuate slightly due to the sensitive nature of the measurement.\r\n-It is advised to repeat the test a few times to ensure consistency in the readings.\r\n\r\n5. Observe the Readings:\r\n-The video shows different values for TOC (0.9 and 0.5), which settle at 0.5 after multiple tests, indicating that this is the accurate reading.\r\n\r\n6. Verify Consistency: \r\n-If the readings stabilize after multiple tests, it can be trusted as accurate.'),
(8, 'Trihalomethanes', '1Qv5BbPKnQw', 'Step to test Total Trihalomethanes (TTHMs) in water using the Hach Total Trihalomethanes (THM) Reagent Set\r\n\r\n1. Collect a Drinking Water Sample\r\n-Prepare the Sample Container. Use a clean, contaminant-free container, preferably a glass bottle or a clean plastic bottle with a tight-fitting lid.\r\n-Collect the Sample. Fill the container with the water sample, ensuring you leave some space at the top to accommodate any air bubbles. Seal the container tightly.\r\n\r\n2. Add Reagents to the Sample:\r\n-Open the THM Reagent Set and retrieve the necessary reagents as indicated in the instructions. Typically, you will need a combination of reagents to react with the THMs present in the sample.\r\n-Follow the reagent addition instructions carefully, as the order and timing of reagent addition are crucial for accurate results.\r\n\r\n3. Mix the Sample:\r\n-After adding the reagents, mix the sample thoroughly. This can be done by gently inverting the vial or using a magnetic stirrer if provided.\r\n\r\n4. Allow the Reaction to Proceed:\r\n-The reaction may require a specific amount of time to develop. This is often outlined in the instructions. During this time, the reagents will react with the THMs, resulting in a color change.\r\n\r\n5. Measure the Absorbance:\r\n-Once the reaction time has elapsed, place the vial in a colorimeter or spectrophotometer, as instructed. The device will measure the color intensity of the sample, which correlates with the concentration of THMs.\r\n-Follow the device\'s instructions for calibration and measurement.\r\n\r\n6. Record the Results:\r\n-The colorimeter or spectrophotometer will display the THM concentration in parts per billion (ppb) or another unit specified by the Hach reagent set.\r\n\r\n7. Interpret Results:\r\n-Compare the result with the standard values provided with the reagent set to determine the concentration of TTHMs in sample.\r\n\r\n8. Dispose of Samples and Reagents Safely:\r\n-Follow the disposal instructions for the used reagents and sample. Many reagents contain chemicals that need to be handled according to safety guidelines.'),
(9, 'Turbidity', '8-txt9LWe-Y', 'Steps for Testing Turbidity with the Apera TN400\r\n\r\n1. Prepare the Sample:\r\n-Collect a water sample in a clean, turbidity-free glass vial. Make sure the vial is clean and free from scratches, as this can affect the readings.\r\n-Fill the vial to the appropriate mark (usually 30 mL) without introducing air bubbles or contaminants.\r\n\r\n2. Clean the Vial:\r\n-Before inserting the vial into the meter, wipe the outside of the vial with a soft, lint-free cloth to remove any fingerprints, smudges, or dust. This ensures that external factors don’t interfere with the measurement.\r\n\r\n3. Calibrate the Meter (if required):\r\n-Calibration is often done using calibration standards provided with the meter (e.g., for 0 NTU, 20 NTU, 100 NTU, and 800 NTU).\r\n-Follow the calibration procedure as outlined in the TN400 manual by placing each standard into the meter and calibrating according to the instructions.\r\n\r\n4. Insert the Sample Vial:\r\n-Place the clean and prepared sample vial into the meter’s sample holder.\r\n-Ensure the vial is properly seated and the meter\'s lid or cover is closed securely to prevent any ambient light from affecting the reading.\r\n\r\n5. Measure the Turbidity:\r\n-Turn on the meter by pressing the power button.\r\n-Press the measurement button to begin the test.\r\n-The meter will display the turbidity value in NTU (Nephelometric Turbidity Units) on the screen.\r\n\r\n6. Repeat if Necessary:\r\nIf you get inconsistent readings, it might be due to air bubbles or particulate matter. Gently shake the sample (without introducing air) and retest if needed.\r\n\r\n7. Record the Results:\r\n-Once the turbidity value is stable, note the reading.\r\n\r\n8. Clean After Use:\r\nAfter completing the test, clean the vial thoroughly to ensure accurate results for future tests.');

