INSERT INTO `variabledetail` (`id`, `title`, `description`, `image_path`, `is_remote`) VALUES
(1, 'pH', 'PH is an important parameter in evaluating the acid–base balance of water. It is also the indicator of acidic or alkaline condition of water status. WHO has recommended maximum permissible limit of pH from 6.5 to 8.5. The current investigation ranges were 6.52–6.83 which are in the range of WHO standards.\n\nLow pH (Acidic): \nWater with a pH below 6.5 can be corrosive and may leach metals such as iron, lead, and copper from pipes, which can lead to health risks and an unpleasant metallic taste.\n\nHigh pH (Alkaline): \nWater with a pH above 8.5 may result in a bitter taste and reduced effectiveness of disinfectants like chlorine, which could potentially allow harmful microorganisms to persist in the water.', 'image1', 0),
(2, 'Hardness', 'Hardness is mainly caused by calcium and magnesium salts. These salts are dissolved from geologic deposits through which water travels. The length of time water is in contact with hardness producing material helps determine how much hardness there is in raw water. Hardness was originally defined as the capacity of water to precipitate soap caused by Calcium and Magnesium.\n\nSoft Water (0–60 mg/L):\nGentle on skin, clothes, and appliances. May feel slippery and lacks essential minerals. No significant health risks, but the absence of minerals offers no health benefits either.\n\nModerately Hard Water (61–120 mg/L):\nGenerally safe and manageable for most uses. Minor scaling in appliances, but it doesn\'t pose significant health or potability issues.\n\nHard Water (121–180 mg/L):\nAffects washing efficiency and causes soap scum. Scaling can occur in plumbing. Still potable but may be unpleasant for daily use.\n\nVery Hard Water (>180 mg/L)\nSignificant scaling in pipes and appliances. Reduces appliance lifespan and efficiency. Potable but may cause dryness of skin and hair. Often requires softening for better quality.', 'image2', 0),
(3, 'Solids (Total dissolved solids - TDS)', 'Water has the ability to dissolve a wide range of inorganic and some organic minerals or salts such as potassium, calcium, sodium, bicarbonates, chlorides, magnesium, sulfates etc. These minerals produced un-wanted taste and diluted color in appearance of water. This is the important parameter for the use of water. The water with high TDS value indicates that water is highly mineralized. Desirable limit for TDS is 500 mg/l and maximum limit is 1000 mg/l which prescribed for drinking purpose.\n\nLow TDS (0–300 ppm):\nExcellent for drinking. Water is fresh and safe for consumption, with a balanced mineral content.\n\nModerate TDS (300–600 ppm):\nGood for drinking, though some may notice a slight taste. It’s still safe and potable.\n\nHigh TDS (600–900 ppm):\nFair for drinking. Water may start to taste salty or bitter. Though still potable, it may not be pleasant for regular consumption.\n\nVery High TDS (900–1200 ppmp):\nPoor for drinking. High mineral content can affect taste and potentially cause issues like dehydration in some individuals. Might require treatment for improved quality.\n\nExtremely High TDS (>1200 ppm):\nNot recommended for drinking. Water contains excessive levels of dissolved solids, which can affect taste and lead to potential health risks over time.', 'image3', 0),
(4, 'Chloramines', 'Chlorine and chloramine are the major disinfectants used in public water systems. Chloramines are most commonly formed when ammonia is added to chlorine to treat drinking water. Chlorine levels up to 4 milligrams per liter (mg/L or 4 parts per million (ppm)) are considered safe in drinking water.\n\nLow Chloramine (0–4 ppm):\nSafe and acceptable for drinking water. The EPA sets 4 ppm as the maximum allowable limit for chloramines in drinking water. At this level, water is effectively disinfected while remaining safe for human consumption.\n\nHigh Chloramine (>4 ppm):\nExceeds the recommended safety limit. Drinking water with chloramine levels above 4 ppm can cause irritation to the skin, eyes, and respiratory system. Prolonged exposure may lead to more serious health issues, especially in individuals with sensitive health conditions (e.g., kidney problems or respiratory issues).', 'image4', 0),
(5, 'Sulfate', 'Sulfates are naturally occurring substances that are found in minerals, soil, and rocks. They are present in ambient air, groundwater, plants, and food. The principal commercial use of sulfate is in the chemical industry. Sulfate concentration in seawater is about 2,700 milligrams per liter (mg/L). It ranges from 3 to 30 mg/L in most freshwater supplies, although much higher concentrations (1000 mg/L) are found in some geographic locations.\n\nLow Sulfate (0–250 mg/L):\nSafe for drinking water. The EPA recommends a maximum limit of 250 mg/L for sulfate in drinking water primarily due to taste concerns. At this level, water is generally safe and potable, though high sulfate levels can have a slightly bitter taste.\n\nHigh Sulfate (>250 mg/L):\nWater may have a noticeable bitter or salty taste, which can cause gastrointestinal issues such as diarrhea, especially in people not accustomed to it. Prolonged exposure to high sulfate levels can also lead to dehydration, particularly in infants and sensitive individuals.', 'image5', 0),
(6, 'Conductivity', 'Pure water is not a good conductor of electric current rather’s a good insulator. Increase in ions concentration enhances the electrical conductivity of water. Generally, the amount of dissolved solids in water determines the electrical conductivity. Electrical conductivity (EC) actually measures the ionic process of a solution that enables it to transmit current. According to WHO standards, EC value should not exceeded 400 μS/cm.\n\nLow Conductivity (0–500 µS/cm):\nIdeal for drinking water. Low conductivity indicates low levels of dissolved salts, which is generally good for taste and potability. It reflects good water quality.\n\nModerate (500–1,500 µS/cm):\nAcceptable for drinking. Conductivity at this level suggests moderate salt levels, which may affect taste but doesn\'t pose significant health risks. Still considered potable for most uses.\n\nHigh Conductivity (1,500–2,500 µS/cm):\nWater quality may be compromised. High conductivity indicates higher levels of dissolved salts, which can affect taste, increase scaling in appliances, and lead to potential health concerns for individuals on low-sodium diets.\n\nVery High Conductivity (>2,500 µS/cm):\nNot recommended for drinking. Conductivity at this level indicates very high levels of dissolved salts, which can lead to a salty or bitter taste and long-term health risks such as hypertension and kidney stress. Treatment or filtration is recommended.', 'image6', 0),
(7, 'Organic_carbon', 'Total Organic Carbon (TOC) in source waters comes from decaying natural organic matter (NOM) as well as synthetic sources. TOC is a measure of the total amount of carbon in organic compounds in pure water. According to US EPA < 2 mg/L as TOC in treated / drinking water, and < 4 mg/Lit in source water which is use for treatment.\n\nLow TOC (0–2 ppm):\nExcellent for drinking water. Low TOC indicates a low presence of organic matter, reducing the potential for harmful byproducts like Trihalomethanes (THMs) during disinfection. Water is safe and of high quality.\n\nModerate TOC (2–4 ppm):\nGenerally safe for drinking, but higher TOC levels increase the likelihood of forming disinfection byproducts (DBPs) like THMs and haloacetic acids (HAAs), which can pose health risks. Monitoring and controlling disinfection methods are recommended.\n\nHigh TOC (4–5 ppm):\nImpact: Water may still be potable but with increased risk. At these levels, organic matter in water is high enough to raise concern about the formation of DBPs, which are linked to potential long-term health effects like cancer or reproductive issues.\n\nVeri High TOC (>5 ppm):\nImpact: Poor water quality. High TOC can lead to excessive DBP formation during disinfection. This makes the water unsuitable for drinking without treatment, as prolonged exposure to DBPs can have serious health implications.', 'image7', 0),
(8, 'Trihalomethanes', 'THMs are chemicals which may be found in water treated with chlorine. The concentration of THMs in drinking water varies according to the level of organic material in the water, the amount of chlorine required to treat the water, and the temperature of the water that is being treated. THM levels up to 80 ppm is considered safe in drinking water.\n\nLow THMs (0–80 µg/L):\nSafe for drinking. The EPA sets a maximum contaminant level (MCL) of 80 µg/L for total THMs in drinking water. At this level, water is considered safe, and health risks are minimal. THM levels are controlled to reduce long-term exposure risks.\n\nHigh THMs (>80 µg/L):\nExceeds the safety limit. Prolonged exposure to higher levels of THMs has been linked to increased risks of cancer (especially bladder cancer), liver and kidney issues, and reproductive problems. Water with THMs above 80 µg/L may require additional treatment or filtration to reduce these byproducts.', 'image8', 0),
(9, 'Turbidity', 'The turbidity of water depends on the quantity of solid matter present in the suspended state. It is a measure of light emitting properties of water and the test is used to indicate the quality of waste discharge with respect to colloidal matter. The mean turbidity value obtained for Wondo Genet Campus (0.98 NTU) is lower than the WHO recommended value of 5.00 NTU.\r\n\r\nLow Turbidity (0–5 NTU):\r\nExcellent water quality. Low turbidity indicates clear water with minimal particles. Water is considered safe for drinking and free from significant contaminants.\r\n\r\nModerate Turbidity (5–10 NTU):\r\nAcceptable for drinking water. Slightly cloudy water may be present but generally safe. Higher levels may affect taste and appearance but are unlikely to pose immediate health risks.\r\n\r\nHigh Turbidity (10–50 NTU):\r\nWater quality is compromised. Noticeable cloudiness can affect the water\'s taste, appearance, and may indicate the presence of harmful microorganisms or contaminants. Treatment or filtration is recommended to improve water quality.\r\n\r\nVery Hiigh Turbidity (>50 NTU):\r\nPoor water quality. Very cloudy water can harbor pathogens and contaminants, making it unsafe for drinking without treatment. High turbidity can indicate severe contamination and requires immediate action to purify the water.', 'image9', 0),
(10, 'Potability', 'Indicates if water is safe for human consumption. Water is considered potable if it meets safety standards that protect against health risks and is deemed acceptable for drinking. Summary:\r\n\r\n1. Water Hardness:\r\n- Soft Water (0–60 mg/L): Safe and gentle; no health risks, but may lack essential minerals.\r\n- Moderately Hard Water (61–120 mg/L): Generally safe; minor scaling and soap lathering issues but no significant health risks.\r\n- Hard Water (121–180 mg/L): Safe but may affect washing and cause scaling; minor health effects.\r\n- Very Hard Water (>180 mg/L): Safe but can cause significant scaling; may lead to skin and appliance issues.\r\n\r\n2. Total Dissolved Solids (TDS):\r\n- 0–300 mg/L: Excellent; water is fresh and safe.\r\n- 300–600 mg/L: Good; safe for drinking with slight taste differences.\r\n- 600–900 mg/L: Fair; may affect taste and could be less ideal for drinking.\r\n- >900 mg/L: Not recommended; high levels may pose health risks.\r\n\r\n3. Chloramines:\r\n- 0–4 ppm: Safe; meets regulatory standards and is effective for disinfection.\r\n- >4 ppm: Exceeds safety limits; may cause health issues like irritation and requires treatment.\r\n\r\n4. Sulfate:\r\n- 0–250 mg/L: Safe; acceptable taste and potability.\r\n- >250 mg/L: May affect taste and cause gastrointestinal issues; treatment may be needed.\r\n\r\n5. Conductivity:\r\n- 0–500 µS/cm: Ideal; low dissolved salts and safe for drinking.\r\n- 500–1,500 µS/cm: Acceptable; moderate salts, safe but may affect taste.\r\n- 1,500–2,500 µS/cm: Water quality may be compromised; higher salts could affect health.\r\n- >2,500 µS/cm: Not recommended; high salts can pose health risks.\r\n\r\n6. Total Organic Carbon (TOC):\r\n- 0–2 ppm: Excellent; low risk of disinfection byproducts.\r\n- 2–4 ppm: Safe but may require monitoring due to potential byproducts.\r\n- >4 ppm: Higher risk of disinfection byproducts; may need treatment.\r\n\r\n7. Trihalomethanes (THMs):\r\n- 0–80 µg/L: Safe; within regulatory limits.\r\n- >80 µg/L: Exceeds safety limits; potential health risks such as cancer and requires treatment.\r\n\r\n8. Turbidity:\r\n- 0–5 NTU: Excellent; clear water, safe for drinking.\r\n- 5–10 NTU: Acceptable; slightly cloudy but generally safe.\r\n- 10–50 NTU: Compromised; may affect safety and requires treatment.\r\n- >50 NTU: Poor; indicates significant contamination, unsafe for drinking without treatment.', 'image10', 0);
COMMIT;

